    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>NGC 5044 is the central dominant galaxy in the X-ray brightest group in the sky.  
Our ALMA cycle 0 observation of CO(2-1) shows that even though the hot X-ray emitting 
gas has been perturbed by multiple AGN outbursts, the cooling flow is still a breeding 
ground for molecular gas with a total mass of 4.0e7 Mo.  Due to the proximity of NGC 5044 
compared to more distant cooling flow clusters, the CO(2-1) emission is resolved into at 
least 30 molecular complexes with individual masses as low as 4.0e5 Mo.  There are no 
disk-like structures suggesting that the molecular gas follows ballistic trajectories 
after condensing out of the cooling flow.  There is also an absorption feature seen against the 
central continuum source with an infalling velocity of 250 km/s.  The wealth of information 
obtained about the molecular gas in NGC 5044 from our 28.5 min cycle 0 observation demonstrates 
the great potential for higher resolution and sensitivity CO(2-1) observations in cycle 2.  
We propose to mosaic the central 5x5 kpc region with the 12m array in cycle 2 covering the 
brightest Ha and [CII] emission, which is a good tracer of molecular gas.       
</prp:abstract>
